   <h1>Re: [VB] Passing of a friend</h1>
   <b>Sean Dorman &lt;croftyest_at_yahoo_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2002-03-26 15:59:23+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>I know how you feel. I lost my best friend and by far
the best german bus accessory, Ben, a German
Shorthair, in November. I raised him from a pup and he
too grew up traveling in my 65 Westfalia. That dog was
more traveled than most people I know and I swear if
he had thumbs I would have had to hide the keys
because I think he would have taken her out when I
wasn't looking! Hang in there, he would!

Sean
65 Westfalia
--- Dave Jersey <arborman_at_hotmail_dot_com> wrote:
> I can finally write about this.
> 
> I met him 3 years ago at High Country Bus Fest.  He
> was in the company of 2 very lovely ladies but he
> caught my eye even more than they did.  I remember
> thinking 'Wow - he's beautiful'.  I tried to get to
> know him but he remained aloof, preferring the
> company of others.  I met him at several other
> campouts, always with the same 2 pretty ladies.  He
> seemed wary of me for some reason, why I didn't
> know.
> 
> About a year ago I went to pick up a bus from one of
> the aforementioned pretty ladies and there he was
> again.  I left busless, but he came home with me. 
> He seemed uneasy during the ride, moving around and
> looking out the window.
> 
> We got to know each other slowly, as most good
> relationships start.  He stayed at the farm while I
> commuted back and forth from Charleston and work to
> my little postage stamp farm in Lenoir, NC.  Every
> Friday when I walked in the door there he was to
> greet me, always happy that I was home and never
> mind what kind of week he may have had.
> 
> If nothing else in the whole wide world, he liked to
> ride in the buses.  I'd ask if he wanted to go with
> me and he'd be at the bus before I was.  He
> tolerated the baywindow camper, but his true love
> (besides me) was the splittie.  He'd sit tall and
> proud, and I know other people would look at him
> riding in the bus with me and they'd marvel too.
> 
> Many of you east coast bussers may have seen him
> either with Andrea and Chris, or with my family and
> I.
> 
> You see, Rocky was much more than a dog, he was a
> great bus person and a great friend.  I have other
> dogs, but it just isn't the same.  I know there are
> other bus dogs out there and have had the honor of
> meeting many of them.
> 
> Driving the bus just isn't the same without him.
> 
> Dave Jersey
> "I read somewhere that 77 per cent of all the
> mentally ill live in poverty. Actually, I'm more
> intrigued
> by the 23 per cent who are apparently doing quite
> well
> for themselves."
>     --Jerry Garcia (Grateful Dead)
> 
> 


__________________________________________________
